The ever-increasing requirement on wireless data rates has been motivating technological innovations on wireless communications in both academia and industry. Among emerging research and development trends in wireless communications, Terahertz Band (0.1??10 THz) communication has been envisioned as one of the key enabling technologies in the next decade. With the ultra-wide available spectrum resources, THz band can provide terabits per second (Tbps) links for a plethora of applications, ranging from ultra-fast massive data transfer among nearby devices in Terabit Wireless Personal and Local Area Networks to high-definition videoconferencing among mobile devices in small cells. 



The research objective of this project is to strengthen the theoretical foundations of ultra-broadband communications in the THz band and bring the Tbps links one-step closer to reality. The targeted breakthrough is to increase the capacity of wireless systems to reach Tbps and overcome the spectrum scarcity and capacity limitations of current wireless networks. In the outcomes report, the research work resulting from the project focuses on solving the following problems:



1)    Design of the plasmonic nanoantennas and nano-transceivers for ultra-massive MIMO communication platform;

2)    Three-Dimensional (3D) Terahertz band channel modeling for indoor propagation environments;

3)    Distance-aware bandwidth-adaptive resource allocation scheme for THz band communication networks;

4)    Development of algorithms for timing acquisition in the THz band;

5)    Channel modeling for UM MIMO systems using the Array-of-Subarray (AoSA) architecture;

6)    Time-varying channel modeling and tracking approach in 3-D indoor environments for THz band communication systems;

7)    Proposition and comparison of four solutions to combating the transmission distance limitation problem in THz bands;

8)    Multi-Band Ultra-Massive MIMO System Design and Characterization;

9)    Multi-Band Communication and Channel Modeling in the Internet of Space Things;

10) Design of intelligent environments based on UM MIMO platforms for mm-wave and THz bands;

11) Channel modeling for THz band communications in dense urban scenario;

12) Beamforming design for advanced communication solution of intelligent environments based on UM MIMO communications.



These new findings in this project have greatly increased our knowledge of both theoretical and practical aspects in THz Band communication networks. The outcomes from the this project bring us one step closer towards the realization of ultra-broadband communication networks in the THz Band. Furthermore, to motivate future research on THz band communications, we study and propose several open research problems, along with the state-of-the-art solutions in enabling Tbps-level throughput for the next-generation wireless communication networks. For the broader impact of the project, the research results are incorporated into the Information and Network Theory and Wireless Communication and Networks within the School of Electrical and Computer Engineering, at the Georgia Institute of Technology, both at undergraduate and graduate levels. Three PhD students have been involved and trained to be- come experts in this fast-evolving field. Master students have also participated in specific sub-problems within the project. The research results are reported and disseminated in first-rate scientific conferences, journals and premier magazines of the field.



